04909nam a22007455i 9781512803808DE-B159720210927121507.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210927t20161970pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)980258603  a97815128038087 a10.9783/97815128038082doi  a(DE-B1597)476614  a(OCoLC)979760404  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aZ1035.4b.L5 7aLAN0270002bisacsh04a028/.9/09421 aLievsay, John L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Englishman's Italian Books, 1550-1700 /cJohn L. Lievsay.  aReprint 2016 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2016] 4c©1970  a1 online resource (120 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPublications of the A. S. W. Rosenbach Fellowship in Bibliography00tFrontmatter -- tPREFACE -- tCONTENTS -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tI. English Printers, Italian Texts -- tII. Italian Books on English Shelves -- tIII. Horner’s Plum: Tomaso Garzoni -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this learned and delightful book, John L. Lievsay shows how energetic English printers of the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries helped to bring the language and literature of Italy into England. His description of how these men, who were not usually troubled by modesty and sometimes not by honesty, capitalized on and helped to create the Englishman's appetite for things Italian will be welcomed by scholars; his analysis of the contents of libraries and catalogues and his commentary on the books themselves will be relished by those who enjoy the scholarship and the gossip behind the collecting and printing of books.In his first essay, "English Printers, Italian Texts," the author identifies the printers and the variety of Italian authors. Torriano's proverbs and Florio's language manuals met a receptive audience. John Wolfe published Pietro Aretino under false imprint, inventing fictional places of publication, and his printings of Machiavelli, suppressed in Italy and not generally available in translation, were highly successful. John Bill, King's Printer, even published an Italian translation of Bacon's Essay.Lievsay then turns to the Italian titles found in library collections of the time, among them Thomas James's catalogs of the Bodleian Library, the bookseller Robert Martin's lists, and the libraries of eminent Englishmen, including those of John Locke and Sir Edward Coke. Lord Herbert's library held a book by "Partenio Etiro," an anagram for Aretino. The work of Tomaso Garzoni has been neglected, but Lievsay revives it in the third essay with descriptions of Garzoni's immensely popular Piazza and Theatro; and "ations from his Mirabile cornutopia—a mock letter of consolation to cuckolds—are evidence of the high spirit of this learned and bizarre man.The essays are based on lectures given at the University of Pennsylvania in the spring of 1969 for the A. S. W. Rosenbach Fellowship in Bibliography.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aEarly printed bookszGreat Britainy16th centuryvBibliography. 0aEarly printed bookszGreat Britainy17th centuryvBibliography. 0aItalian imprintszEngland. 0aPublishers and publishingzGreat Britain. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Publishing.2bisacsh  aLibrary Science and Publishing.  aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Package Archive 1898-1999z978311044252640uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978151280380840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781512803808423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781512803808/original  a978-3-11-044252-6  University of Pennsylvania Press Package Archive 1898-1999c1898d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LB  aEBA_EB